segments.text: Mostly gardening at that time.
Vegetable gardening?
I tried that with little success.
Did it shift into flowers?
No, I never did much with flowers.
Where did you go to celebrate?
Celebrate?
I don't remember any celebration.
You know a guy whom I haven't mentioned?

celebration makes me think of it because for some obscure reason I thought then Mennonite who the devil was the guy the general who moved into the office at my invitation oh such a wonderful loyal person I'm embarrassed that I his name no no the guy who became head of the health service here then after he left the dean's office
Oh my, that's really embarrassing.

You know the man, he's been active in Kiwanis or Lyons or whatever, all kinds of activities around town, very generous, but from a Mennonite background, I may have the sect a little wrong, terrible tragedies in his life, two of his children committed suicide, his wife was a depressive
But he was always of good cheer.
He'd been chief in San Antonio of a hospital down there.
What the devil?
Pathologist.
Gosh, I've got to remember his name because somewhere he needs to get some accolades or recognition or something.
Loyal, warm, kind person.
Hard worker.
All right.
If you were giving advice to today's administrators about the medical school, what advice would you give them?
Well, I'm out of touch, so it wouldn't be specific.
It would be more kind of process.
And I think that, now it depends on the level.
At the level of university administration, I don't know what you all do when you get together and talk or when they have those meetings for the new presidents.
And I don't know the extent to which medicine is special.
For me, it's very special.
But I don't know the extent that it's more special problem or opportunity for a president than engineering or whatever.
I think the university presidents need to have much broader understanding, I'm going to stick with medicine, of medical education in other institutions.
That to me was the most stultifying thing here, that the people with whom I was dealing knew nothing about medical education and didn't want to learn.
Now, at the level of the medical school deans,

I really think there is, although they talk about experiments in medical education, there is a very active group called RIME, Research in Medical Education, yet medical education is frozen into a frame of reference.
And there are very few real experiments in medical education.
One of them, incidentally, is in New Mexico.
which I didn't initiate, but I fostered and it came out of the faculty.
It's still going on and it's truly distinguished.
But I did nothing except get out of the way of that.
If you were organizing administratively this institution and its medical school, where would you place the medical school administratively?
Yeah, that's a perennial problem.
And I think the answer, I guess it sounds like a pretty soft answer.
The answer is not in the structure.
It is in the relationships among the people.
It is not in the structure.
Would you have that report, would it be part of the university or part of the system?
I won't do that.
I won't do that because I don't believe it's structural, Haskell.
I believe that
while you might need to have a table of organization, every table of organization can and will work.
I'm absolutely adamant about that.
I feel very strongly about it because the debates have been endless.
And one of the problems that my several successors have had is they have come in with traditional views about what their prerogatives were, what the structure should be, and they have come a cropper.
Not just in this university, they went into another university.
I don't know what you had at Missouri.
I visited Missouri when Joe White was still vice president, and they wanted me to... Joe White...
I feel that I was vigorously, enthusiastically recruited at Missouri when Joe White was there.

I never told Joe, but what turned me off and made me absolutely refuse to take that job was Joe White, when he told me that he wanted me to come, he said, the first thing you're going to have to do is fire the chairman of anesthesiology.
Well, that's horse manure.
Would you, again, in this, you're the advisor, you would perhaps reduce the enrollment a little, class size?
Oh, yes, yes, yes.
That would have to be done carefully for financial political reasons.
And that's what makes faculties anywhere nervous, particularly state-funded institutions.
They figure, well, somebody is going to look at that cost per student.
The cost per student is going to go up, and they'll cut our appropriation.
Would you modify the instructional program and add more or less?
No, again, I think that there's been much too much made of that, of engineering the curriculum and giving more hours to this or fewer hours to that or saying that this course has to follow that.
I don't think those are the issues, and yet that's what preoccupies the faculty.
And you would tell the faculty, keep emphasizing what?
I don't want to be buddies with the students.
I don't want the students to call the faculty by their first name, categorically.
But they are faculties to teach, and they have multiple responsibilities.
They are faculties to create, but the students can't be given short shrift.
They cannot, whether it's Harvard or Texas A&M or wherever.
The faculty has to teach.
It's a hard job being a faculty member, tough job.
I wouldn't want it.
Should A&M try to do more in involving local practitioners?
No, no.
There's a good mix there you think?
I think it would be tilting at windmills.
I think it's wasted effort.
In New Mexico I tried
very hard because the medical practice in New Mexico when I was there was primitive.
And we tried to help people and get them involved and provide continuing medical education opportunities.
But those old guys are, and they were guys, not women, are, you know, they were at the bottom of the class to start with, and they still are.
All right, now, what topics have we not touched on?
That's it, sex.
Let's make believe that at some future date someone walked up to you and gave you a check for a million dollars with one restriction.
It must be passed on to Texas A&M.
If you could make a very large contribution to A&M
For what purpose would you want it?
A million dollars wouldn't do anything.
A million dollars buys one professor.
If you could make a substantial gift, what would it be for?
In your gizzard, what are you most concerned about?
For a while, a national group that I was involved with
was doing something that wasn't unique to medical education, but leadership development and serious attention.
I got some of this at the Sloan School, in fact quite a bit.
I did a fair bit of third party consulting while I was at Sloan School.
You probably know Bennis, Warren Bennis,
even consulted with him, with Paul Lawrence and I went out to the University of Cincinnati when he was there and having trouble.
What I believe, I believe that really good
behavioral science, I guess I would say, emphasis on behavioral science.
That's the background that I got from Harvard and MIT working with Paul Lawrence who was at Harvard.
That's what I think faculty needs more than accounting

or good business practices or other highly structured relationships, when one looks at the good managers in industry, they've been guys who've walked around the plant, who went down on the floor and talked to the foreman and the men on the assembly line.
I think what I've seen, I think they did that.
They weren't too proud.
And they needed to know.
It was where they got information.
It was where they knew what their organizations were doing.
Can you imagine the president of Texas A&M University coming over and shooting a bull with the dean or the students?
It doesn't happen.
Or the regents?
I'm proud to say that I never missed a semester teaching a freshman class, early on Tuesday and Thursday morning.
So at least I had a little bit of real-world experience.
All right, then, to conclude, in two or three questions, how do you feel about your years at A&M?
Regretful.
What do you mean?
Well, I don't think there's much to show for it.
You don't think that medical school represents some...
It's not a distinguished medical school.
It has some good points, and I suppose like most universities or whatever, whatever we have is the best or the greatest, but it ain't.
On a national scale, this is not a distinguished medical school.
And I'm sorry that that's the case.
Could it have become distinguished in a quarter century?
Well, I don't know.
We don't have a controlled experiment.
Perhaps under different leadership it could have, but that's not the issue that I'm dealing with.
I'm dealing with the reality of what there is there, and what there is there is a medical school in the fourth quartile
of how you might rank medical schools in the country.
But hasn't it made more progress than any of the other brand new ones?
I don't think so.
What do you feel about this institution in general?
About what institution?
Texas A&M?
that the regents, maybe mostly the regents, that the former students do not have a clear understanding that this is not a distinguished university.
They're kidding themselves.
It's not.
It's a big university.
It's the biggest in the world as far as I'm concerned.
But you can count the number of scholars

on one hand, two hands, or the number of distinguished departments, if you look at the rankings wherever they come from, whether it's the number of publications or whatever, it's not of the stature that it should be given the resources that have been put into it.
Are you shaking your head?
That you hear me or that you agree?
No, I'm saying I hear you and I understand the point you make.
Now, do you want to conclude with that point?
What more is there to say?
No, I don't want to conclude with that point because I don't want that on the record.
I don't want anybody else to see that.
Oh, okay.
Well, when it's typed up and we give it back to you.
I'll scratch that out.
All right.
How would you like this interview to end, then?
What statements would you like at the end of it?
That's what I thought I was asking when I was saying, what do you think, how do you feel about this institution in general?
I think that given the milieu, that is given Texas, given the Texas heritage, given what Texas is, that this is about as good as this university can be.
I think in general terms University of Texas in Austin is a more distinguished institution and I don't understand why Texas A&M can't outshine the University of Texas at Austin.
I understand why we're not as good as Rice.
I don't have a problem with that.
I understand why
in many respects we're a better institution than SMU or Baylor.
But why we can't have the student body, of course turning that around a certain number of people will say that's the strength of the institution.
We don't have the student body, the grungy hop
potheads or whatever they are at Austin.
We don't have them.
That's the strength of this university for many of the parents, maybe for many of the faculty, for the regents.
And so what I'm saying is antithetical to exactly what is wanted of Texas A&M University.
It is what the people who have it, who own it, want of it.
This is not the University of Texas at Austin.
Haskell, the last thing I want to say off the record, I apologize
